data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already threw `InvalidOperationException` for sync operations **by default**, but you could opt back in with:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos("...", builder =>
    builder.AllowSynchronousIO());
```

**In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** The Cosmos DB provider is now async-only — `AllowSynchronousIO()` no longer exists, so all four of your sync calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

## What to change

Convert to async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- All methods in `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` namespace
- Callers up the chain must also become `async`/`await` (this ripples up to controllers)
